<DOC><DOCNO> AP890302-0182 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-02-89 2119EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Massacre     03-02 0267</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Colombia-Massacre,0275</SECOND><HEAD>Police Blame Leftist Rebels For Massacre</HEAD><DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A guerrilla's confession and a capturedrebel communique showed that insurgents were responsible for killingan emerald dealer and 18 other people at a ranch this week, policesaid Thursday.   The emerald dealer, Gilberto Molina, was reputedly a vehementanti-communist who allegedly organized death squads to kill peasantswho sympathized with guerrillas.   Authorities say Molina was the target of two previous rebelassassination attempts.   National police said they captured one of the approximately 50guerrillas who were disguised as national policemen when they showedup at Molina's ranch on Monday.   The police have not allowed reporters to see a rebel communiquethat they say points to insurgent involvement in the slaying, or tointerview the alleged guerrilla said to belong to the ColombianRevolutionary Armed Forces.   Killed along with Molina were 14 of his bodyguards, his chief ofsecurity, a business partner of Molina's, a musician and Molina'schauffeur, national police said in the communique issued Thursday.   The attackers showed up at Molina's ranch at 2 a.m. Monday sayingthey were searching for a reputed drug trafficker, Gonzalo RodriguezGacha.   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration says Rodriguez is one ofthe country's biggest drug traffickers. Leftist guerrilla groupshave said Rodriguez helped Molina organize right-wing death squads.   Within 24 hours of the massacre two communist leaders were slainin Bogota in what newspapers in the capital said was revenge for themassacre. The two were Teofilo Forero, the secretary of Colombia'scommunist party, and Antonio Stelo Pineda, a member of the party'scentral committee.</TEXT></DOC>